rdsey (Yorkshire), Rowley in Lepton (Yorkshire), and Rowley Hill (Essex). The placenames probably all derive from Old English <i>rūh</i> ‘rough’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’, though the East Yorkshire place may have been named with <i>hlāw</i> ‘mound, hill’ as the second element.","Irish: from <b>Ó Roghallaigh</b>, a variant of <b>Ó Raghailligh</b>. See   Riley   and   O'Reilly  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rowlee","meanings":["English: variant of   Rowley  ."]},{"name":"Roley","meanings":["English: variant of   Rowley  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Rollie","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish: variant of   Rowley  ."]},{"name":"Riley","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): habitational name chiefly from High Ryley in Accrington (Lancashire) and Riley in Kirkburton, which was in the manor of Wakefield (Yorkshire). In some cases the name may derive from Riley Farm in Eyam (Derbyshire), Royley in Royton (Lancashire), or Rylah in Scarcliffe (Derbyshire). The placenames all come from Old English <i>rȳge</i> ‘rye’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","Irish: from <b>Ó Raghailligh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Raghailleach</i>’, Old Irish <i>Roghallach</i>. This is the name of a chieftain family in Cavan, related to the O'Rourkes. In Anglicized form it has also been confused with <b>Ó Raithile</b> found in Munster, usually Anglicized as <b>O'Rahilly</b> or   Rahilly  . See   O'Reilly  ."]},{"name":"Rolley","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Rowley  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":5,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When John Rowley was born about 1450, in Burslem, Staffordshire, England, his father, John Rowley, was 24 and his mother, Alice Newton, was 18. He had at least 1 daughter with Gylian. He died after 1489, in England."},"et":{"about 1450–after 1489":"umbes 1450–pärast 1489","1450–1489":"1450–1489","1450–Female":"1450–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1490–1594":"1490–1594","1428–Male":"1428–Surnud","1433–1465":"1433–1465","after 1489":"pärast 1489","about 1490":"umbes 1490","1489":"1489","1455":"1455","1433":"1433","1465":"1465","1594":"1594","1450":"1450","1490":"1490","1428":"1428","about 1450":"umbes 1450","Burslem, Staffordshire, England":"Burslem, Staffordshire, England","England":"England","Worfield, Bridgnorth, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Worfield, Shropshire, England","Burslem, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Burslem, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1450–after 1489":"noin 1450–1489 jälkeen","1450–1489":"1450–1489","1450–Female":"1450–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1490–1594":"1490–1594","1428–Male":"1428–Kuollut","1433–1465":"1433–1465","after 1489":"1489 jälkeen","about 1490":"noin 1490","1489":"1489","1455":"1455","1433":"1433","1465":"1465","1594":"1594","1450":"1450","1490":"1490","1428":"1428","about 1450":"noin 1450","Burslem, Staffordshire, England":"Burslem, Staffordshire, England","England":"England","Worfield, Bridgnorth, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Worfield, Shropshire, England","Burslem, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Burslem, Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1450–after 1489":"environ 1450–après 14